h3. Issue Summary

Rate limiting evaluates if the requests are coming from UI by checking some cookies and headers. Some client libraries like [https://pypi.org/project/jira/2.0.0/] keeps the cookies set from the server and following requests are evaluated as UI request and rate limiting is not applied. These requests are shown in the access logs as coming from python agent.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Use the library specified or send back the cookie set two of cookie/header below
{code:java}
public static final String HEADER_ORIGIN = "origin";
public static final String HEADER_REFERER = "Referer";
public static final String COOKIE_SESSION_ID = "JSESSIONID";
public static final String COOKIE_CSRF_TOKEN = "atlassian.xsrf.token"{code}

 # Perform request to rate enabled Jira server
 # Requests are evaluated as UI and not rate limited

h3. Expected Results

Requests coming from specific agents like python are not evaluated as UI requests even if they meet the cookie/header criteria for the UI requests.
h3. Actual Results

Requests are not limited and they can be seen as coming from python client in the access logs
{noformat}
192.168.20.55 272x228079x2 ****** [16/Jun/2021:04:32:05 +0200] "GET /jira/rest/api/2/field HTTP/1.0" 200 12393 161 "-" "python-requests/2.25.1" "1m3clon"
192.168.20.55 272x228080x2 ****** [16/Jun/2021:04:32:05 +0200] "GET /jira/rest/api/2/field HTTP/1.0" 200 12393 155 "-" "python-requests/2.25.1" "160ga5k"
{noformat}
h3. Workaround

Only workaround is to make sure client does not send the cookie/header that will make the request evaluated as UI request.

h3. Issue Summary
After upgrading Jira to version 8.18.0, there is a warning on the header with the following message. 
(i) There is *no* functionality impact besides the non-dismissible warning. The problem is caused by a bug in the license validation library. 

{quote}
(!) The product license you're using is not legitimate. Contact your license issuer.
{quote}

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Upgrade Jira to version 8.18.0
# Locate the warning message on the header

(!) Currently, the problem can only be reproduced in Jira hosted in a Windows environment. For those experiencing this problem in Linux environment, please raise a support ticket with Atlassian Support.

h3. Expected Results
No warning regarding product license upon successful upgrade.

h3. Actual Results
Warning message added on the header.

!license_warning.png!

h3. Workaround
Credit to [~gschoch@gs-soft.com]
# Navigate to …\Atlassian\JIRA\atlassian-jira\WEB-INF\classes\templates\jira\webpanel\notifications and create a backup of the "banner.soy" file
 # Open the "banner.soy" file
 # Remove the following new section (_introduced in with the latest release of JIRA_)
{code:java}
/**
* Render a forged license detected banner
*/
{template .licenseForgedBannerMessage}
    {call aui.message.warning}
        {param content}      
            <div id="license-banner-content">
                {getText('admin.license.banner.forged.warning')}
            </div>     
        {/param}
    {/call}
{/template}{code}
# reboot JIRA

The following artilce has reference to the term "{{<JIRA_SHARED_HOME>/old}} " under the "Failover to the Standby Instance" section:

Below is an excerpt from the documentation:
 * [Disaster Recovery Guide for Jira|https://confluence.atlassian.com/enterprise/disaster-recovery-guide-for-jira-692782022.html] 
{panel}
h3. Step 1. Fail over to the standby instance

The basic steps to failover to the standby instance are:
 # Ensure your live system is shutdown and no longer updating the database.
 # Ensure that the directory {{<JIRA_SHARED_HOME>/old}} does *not* exist on the standby instance.{panel}


Initially, the folder named "old" stored the index archive. 
It was decided to change this name to "indexarchive", but the documentation was not updated and it still contains an outdated folder name: "old".

Kindly update the documentation and replace "{{<JIRA_SHARED_HOME>/old}}{{" with }}
{{"<JIRA_SHARED_HOME>/indexarchive."}}

h3. Issue Summary

b as a shortcut does not work and creates red warning at the top of the page.

!image-2021-06-17-15-17-19-974.png!
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Go to backlog / board view
 # Click b
 # Red warning appears on the top of the page

h3. Expected Results

Either a desired action is performed or nothing should happen.
h3. Actual Results

The below exception is thrown in the xxxxxxx.log file:
{noformat}
Exception: Uncaught TypeError: GH.Shortcut.focusBoardSearch is not a functionResource: https://my-secret-jira.com/secure/RapidBoard.jspa?rapidView=1081&useStoredSettings=true{noformat}
{noformat}
Line: 371{noformat}
{noformat}
Column: 26454
{noformat}
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

Currently we have REST API which returns the details for a given project role in a project.

[Get project role|https://docs.atlassian.com/software/jira/docs/api/REST/8.13.3/#api/2/project/\{projectIdOrKey}/role-getProjectRole]
{code:java}
GET /rest/api/2/project/{projectIdOrKey}/role/{id}{code}
However this is specific to a project. Customer would like to find information across multiple projects which is possible using SQL provided in [How to list all users by project role in Jira.|https://confluence.atlassian.com/jirakb/how-to-list-all-users-by-project-role-in-jira-1041077920.html]

Having a REST API for finding projects where a user is project administrator would be useful.
